er popular protest in all regions of Japan and to encompass nearly three centuries of history, from the beginnings of the Tokugawa shogunate in the 1590s to the Meiji restoration.White applies contemporary sociological theory to evidence previously unavailable in English. He draws on the long historical record of peasant uprisings, using narrative interpretation and sophisticated quantitative analysis. By linking the texture of conflict to the political and economic regime the shoguns created, he casts doubt on competing interpretations of a contained, orderly society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aPeasant uprisingszJapanxHistory. 0aSocial conflictzJapanxHistory. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311066589508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501704598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501704598.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  a978-3-11-060673-7  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017c2016d2017  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  a978-3-11-066589-5  COR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG